{{Infobox alternative medicine | name = Quantum healing | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | pronounce = | classification = [[Quantum mysticism]] | modality = | claims = quantum phenomena are responsible for health and wellbeing | topics = | origyear = | origprop = [[Deepak Chopra]] | laterprop = | seealso = | MeshID = }} '''Quantum healing''' is a [[Pseudoscience|pseudo-scientific]] mixture of ideas purported to draw on [[quantum mechanics]], [[psychology]], [[philosophy]], and [[neurophysiology]] that asserts that quantum phenomena are responsible for health and wellbeing. There are a number of different versions, which allude to various quantum ideas including [[wave particle duality]] and [[virtual particles]], and more generally "[[energy (esotericism)|energy]]" and [[vibration]]s.<ref>{{cite web |author=Alexander Dunlop |url=http://spiritualnutrition.org/quantum-healing-vibrations |title=Quantum Healing: Transforming Who You Are - Spiritual Life Coaching |publisher=Spiritualnutrition.org |date= |accessdate=2012-12-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121229175240/http://spiritualnutrition.org/quantum-healing-vibrations |archive-date=2012-12-29 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> Quantum healing is a form of [[alternative medicine]].
The term was coined by [[Deepak Chopra]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Work of Andrew Weil and Deepak Chopra-Two Holistic Health/New Age Gurus: A Critique of the Holistic Health/New Age Movements|doi=10.1525/maq.2003.17.2.233}}</ref> His discussions of quantum healing have been characterised as [[technobabble]] - "incoherent babbling strewn with scientific terms"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/answer-sheet/wp/2015/05/15/scientist-why-deepak-chopra-is-driving-me-crazy/ |title=Scientist: Why Deepak Chopra is driving me crazy |last=Strauss |first=Valerie |date=2015-05-15 |work=Washington Post |access-date=2018-05-19 |language=en-US |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> which "drives crazy people who actually understand physics"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2012/nov/23/change-your-life-pseudoscience |title=This column will change your life: pseudoscience |last=Burkeman |first=Oliver |date=2012-11-23 |access-date=2018-05-19 |language=en}}</ref> and "redefining Wrong".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/bad_astronomy/2009/12/01/deepak_chopra_redefining_wrong.html |title=Deepak Chopra: redefining "wrong" |last=Plait |first=Phil |date=2009-12-01 |work=Slate |access-date=2018-05-19 |language=en-US |issn=1091-2339}}</ref>
Quantum healing has a number of vocal followers, but is widely regarded as being nonsensical by the scientific community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2014/05/quantum_consciousness_physics_and_neuroscience_do_not_explain_one_another.html|title=Quantum and Consciousness Often Mean Nonsense|last=Francis|first=Matthew R.|date=2014-05-29|work=Slate|access-date=2018-09-21|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339}}</ref> The main criticism revolves around its systematic misinterpretations of modern [[physics]],<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|last=Cox |first=Brian |url=http://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2012/02/20/why-quantum-theory-is-so-misunderstood/ |title=Why Quantum Theory Is So Misunderstood - Speakeasy - WSJ |publisher=Blogs.wsj.com |date=2012-02-20 |accessdate=2012-12-15}}</ref> especially of the fact that [[macroscopic]] objects (such as the human body or individual cells) are much too large to exhibit inherently quantum properties like [[quantum interference|interference]] and [[wave function collapse]]. Most literature on quantum healing is almost entirely philosophical, omitting the rigorous mathematics that makes [[quantum electrodynamics]] possible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aske-skeptics.org.uk/magic_of_quantum_physics.html |title='Magic' of Quantum Physics |publisher=Aske-skeptics.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-12-15}}</ref>
Physicist [[Brian Cox (physicist)|Brian Cox]] argues that misuse of the word "quantum", such as its use in ''quantum healing'', has a negative effect on [[society]] as it undermines genuine science and discourages people from engaging with conventional medicine. He states that "for some scientists, the unfortunate distortion and misappropriation of scientific ideas that often accompanies their integration into popular culture is an unacceptable price to pay."<ref name="autogenerated1"/>
