{{Refimprove|date=October 2017}} A '''tacit assumption''' or '''implicit assumption''' is an assumption that includes the underlying agreements or statements made in the development of a [[logical argument]], course of action, [[Decision-making|decision]], or [[judgment]] that are not explicitly voiced nor necessarily understood by the decision maker or judge. Often, these assumptions are made based on personal life experiences, and are not consciously apparent in the [[decision making]] environment. These assumptions can be the source of apparent [[paradox]]es, misunderstandings and [[resistance to change]] in human [[organization]]al [[behavior]].
